South African Equities: Anglo, Basil Read, Clicks, Harmony Gold

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a   a n d   R e n e e   B o n o r c h i s
-- 
2011-03-24T17:07:27Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-24/equities-in-south-africa-rise-for-third-day-led-by-bhp-and-anglo-american.html
South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE  Africa  All
Share Index gained for a third day, rising 432.14, or 1.4
percent, to 31,647.69 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Basil Read Holdings Ltd. (BSR)  , the construction and
engineering company, dropped 25 cents, or 2.3 percent, to 10.50
rand, the most in a month. Basil Read said full-year operating
profit fell 5 percent to 408.8 million rand ($59.6 million).  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s largest mining
company, advanced for a second day, adding 2.85 rand, or 1.1
percent, to 262.54 rand.  BHP Billiton  and Rio Tinto Group won
their second mining-tax battle in  Australia  after the government
agreed to allow them to credit future state royalties imposts
against a planned 30 percent levy on their profits.  Anglo
American Plc (AGL)  , the diversified mining company that makes
up 11 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock index, jumped to
the highest since March 9, rising 5.32 rand, or 1.5 percent, to
355.83 rand.  Clicks Group Ltd. (CLS)  , a retailer of toiletries, music
and pharmaceuticals, jumped to the highest level since Jan. 19,
gaining 61 cents, or 1.5 percent, to 41.01 rand. Earnings for
the first half through February will be as much as 25 percent
higher than a year earlier, Clicks said in a trading update.  Hardware Warehouse Ltd. (HWW)  , a building materials
retailer, increased the most in five months, rising 10 cents, or
29 percent, to 45 cents. Earnings after one-time items probably
advanced to as much as 8.51 cents a share in the first half
through December, compared with 0.24 cents a share in the year
earlier, it said in a trading update today.  Harmony Gold Mining Co. Ltd. (HAR SJ), Africa’s third-
largest producer of gold, jumped the most since Nov. 24, 2008,
climbing 10.45 rand, or 12 percent, to 98.40 rand after  RBC
Capital Markets  said the mining company may become a takeover
target.  To contact the reporters on this story:
